From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] amdgpu: v50 - generic ATOM table tracer for modeset diagnosis

After v49 (patch 0023) clobbered Sony's bogus dp_extclk and got the
picker to return ATOM_PPLL2 instead of ATOM_PPLL_INVALID, the v46 trace
showed:

  SetPixelClock IN  ... pll=1 ref=2 fb=118 frac=8 post=22 ...
  SetPixelClock OUT r=0   <-- 355 us after IN (was 22 us in v48)

The 355 us execute time (16x longer than v48's no-op) proves ATOM
bytecode is now actually programming the real Liverpool display PLL
(whatever its real register addresses are). The PLL is healthy.

But the bridge cq_wait_set still hangs 3 seconds polling for DP lane
lock that never asserts. So the GPU is producing some output but the
bridge doesn't see a valid DP signal.

The v46 trace only catches AdjustDisplayPll and SetPixelClock — the two
specific ATOM tables we instrumented. There are ~20 other ATOM tables
that run during modeset (DIGxEncoderControl, UNIPHYTransmitterControl,
EnableCRTC, BlankCRTC, SetCRTC_UsingDTDTiming, EnableScaler,
EnableGraphSurfaces, etc.). We have zero visibility into whether any of
them fire, in what order, or with what return codes.

This patch adds a single hook in amdgpu_atom_execute_table_locked() —
the central function that ALL ATOM table calls go through, both
top-level (from amdgpu_atom_execute_table) and recursive (from
atom_op_calltable opcode handler when a parent table calls a sub-table
via CALL_TABLE bytecode). One trace point catches everything.

The kernel already has a 74-entry atom_table_names[] array (gated by
ATOM_DEBUG, which is defined at the top of atom.c). The trace prints
the index, the human-readable name, parameter size, return value, and
the nesting depth (debug_depth) so we can see parent/child relationships.

Expected next-boot output (illustrative — actual table set depends on
DCE 8.x DP path):

  ps4_atom_table: [d=0] enter idx=0x4d (?) ps_size=8
    ps4_atom_table: [d=1] enter idx=... (sub-table)
    ps4_atom_table: [d=1] exit  idx=... ret=0
  ps4_atom_table: [d=0] exit  idx=0x4d (?) ret=0
  ps4_atom_table: [d=0] enter idx=0x0c (SetPixelClock) ps_size=24
  ps4_atom_table: [d=0] exit  idx=0x0c (SetPixelClock) ret=0
  ps4_atom_table: [d=0] enter idx=0x22 (BlankCRTC) ...
  ps4_atom_table: [d=0] enter idx=0x23 (EnableCRTC) ...
  ...

After the next boot we'll know the complete sequence between
SetPixelClock and the bridge's second cq_wait_set, including any tables
that should run but don't, or run but return non-zero. That will
identify the real failure point inside the GPU's DP TX / DIG / CRTC
enable path.

Note on log volume: each modeset triggers ~20-50 master+sub table
calls, ASIC_Init at boot triggers ~50-100. Each line is one pr_info, so
~150 extra log lines per boot. Acceptable for diagnosis. Once we
identify the failing table, this patch should be removed or gated.

The trace is unconditional (no asic_type guard) because (a)
amdgpu_atom_execute_table_locked has no easy access to asic_type, (b)
the prefix "ps4_atom_table:" makes log filtering trivial, and (c) the
tracer's only consumer right now is PS4 hardware. If repurposed for a
non-Liverpool build later, comment out or wrap in a Kconfig.

---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/atom.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/atom.c
@@ -1234,9 +1234,23 @@
 	unsigned char op;
 	atom_exec_context ectx;
 	int ret = 0;
-
-	if (!base)
+	/* v50: trace every ATOM master/sub table call so we can see the
+	 * sequence of tables fired during modeset on Liverpool. debug_depth
+	 * indicates nesting (top-level call = 0, sub-table from
+	 * atom_op_calltable = 1+). atom_table_names[] is from atom-names.h
+	 * gated by ATOM_DEBUG, which is defined at top of this file. */
+	int my_depth = debug_depth;
+	const char *tname = (index < ATOM_TABLE_NAMES_CNT) ?
+			    atom_table_names[index] : "?";
+
+	pr_info("ps4_atom_table: [d=%d] enter idx=0x%02x (%s) ps_size=%d\n",
+		my_depth, index, tname, params_size);
+
+	if (!base) {
+		pr_info("ps4_atom_table: [d=%d] exit  idx=0x%02x (%s) ret=-EINVAL (no base)\n",
+			my_depth, index, tname);
 		return -EINVAL;
+	}

 	len = CU16(base + ATOM_CT_SIZE_PTR);
 	ws = CU8(base + ATOM_CT_WS_PTR);
@@ -1290,6 +1304,8 @@
 free:
 	if (ws)
 		kfree(ectx.ws);
+	pr_info("ps4_atom_table: [d=%d] exit  idx=0x%02x (%s) ret=%d\n",
+		my_depth, index, tname, ret);
 	return ret;
 }

